  "opinion": "As an 83-year-old man living in Rome, retired and with a life rich in experiences from raising four children and immigrating here, I've seen how the world has changed, especially with social media. I spend about an hour daily on platforms like Facebook, mostly to keep up with family photos and travel stories, but I've noticed more fake content popping up. Managing it starts with a simple, old-fashioned approach: trust your gut and don't believe everything you see. With my moderate openness, I'm curious but cautious; I learned long ago that not all information is reliable, much like stories passed down in my immigrant community. My low conscientiousness means I'm not overly systematic, so I rely on common sense—if a post seems too sensational or doesn't match what I know from my travels or painting, I question it. For example, I once saw a fake news story about a famous landmark in Rome, and I knew it was wrong because I've painted it myself. I think social media companies should do more to filter this stuff, but as users, we have a role too. I talk to my children about it, using our family chats to fact-check things, which helps given my low agreeableness—I'm not afraid to challenge what I see. My Christian beliefs guide me to seek truth and avoid spreading lies, so I rarely share posts unless I'm sure. In short, dealing with fake content is about staying skeptical, leaning on personal experience, and using social media wisely without letting it overwhelm you, which fits my good mental health and moderate neuroticism—I don't get too stressed by it.",
